{# templates/roadmaps/retirement/the-4-percent-rule.html.twig #}
{% extends 'base-roadmaps.html.twig' %}

        {% block stylesheets %}
        {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_link_tags('retirement_css') }}
    {% endblock %}

    {% block javascripts %}
    {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_script_tags('retirement_js') }}
    {% endblock %}

    {% block body %}
    <div class="container">
    <!-- article hero – retirement style -->
    <div class="article-hero animate" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e1a3a 0%, #2d2b55 100%);">
        <div class="hero-content">
            <div class="hero-icon" style="background-color: var(--retirement-color);">
                <i class="fas fa-calculator"></i>
            </div>
            <h1>The 4% Rule <span>Your Retirement Number</span></h1>
            <p class="hero-description">
                How much money do you actually need to retire comfortably? The 4% Rule is a simple, time‑tested guideline that gives you a clear target. Learn how it works and calculate your personal number.
            </p>
            <div class="phase-tag" style="background-color: rgba(108,92,231,0.2); color: #c3b9ff;">
                <i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> Phase 1: Foundation First · 9 min read
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- introduction -->
    <section class="animate">
        <h2 class="section-title">🧮 What is the 4% Rule?</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">
            The <strong>4% Rule</strong> is a retirement withdrawal guideline developed from the Trinity Study. It states that if you withdraw 4% of your portfolio in your first year of retirement, and adjust that amount for inflation each year thereafter, your savings should last at least 30 years – even in tough markets.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 1.1rem;">
            In simple terms: <strong>Your target nest egg = Your annual retirement spending ÷ 0.04</strong>.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- key insights in rule‑grid style -->
    <div class="rule-grid animate">
        <div class="rule-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-history"></i> Origin</h4>
            <p>Based on the Trinity Study (1998), which analyzed historical market returns to find a safe withdrawal rate that would have survived various 30‑year periods.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-percent"></i> The 4% Figure</h4>
            <p>With a portfolio of 60% stocks and 40% bonds, a 4% initial withdrawal rate had a high success rate historically. It’s a starting point, not a guarantee.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-sync-alt"></i> Inflation Adjustment</h4>
            <p>After year one, you increase your withdrawal by the previous year’s inflation rate to maintain purchasing power.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rule-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Caveats</h4>
            <p>Future returns may differ; taxes, fees, and a longer retirement (e.g., early retirement) may require a more conservative rate like 3.5% or 3%.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- interactive tool: 4% Rule Calculator -->
    <div class="card animate" style="margin: 40px 0;" id="four-percent-tool">
        <h3><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> Interactive: Find Your Retirement Number</h3>
        <p>Enter your desired annual spending in retirement (in today’s dollars) and adjust the withdrawal rate to see the nest egg you’ll need.</p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
            <div style="flex: 1 1 250px;">
                <label>Annual spending in retirement ($)</label>
                <input type="number" id="annualSpending" value="40000" step="1000" min="0" class="cat-input" style="width:100%;">
            </div>
            <div style="flex: 1 1 250px;">
                <label>Withdrawal rate (%) <span id="withdrawalRateVal">4.0</span></label>
                <input type="range" id="withdrawalRate" min="2" max="6" value="4" step="0.1" class="cat-input" style="width:100%;">
            </div>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
            <button id="calculateFourPercent" class="btn-outline">Calculate required nest egg</button>
        </div>

        <div id="fourPercentResult" style="margin-top: 25px; padding: 20px; background: var(--light-color); border-radius: 12px;">
            <p>Adjust the values and click the button.</p>
        </div>

        <div id="withdrawalComparison" style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 15px; background: #e9e5ff; border-radius: 12px; display: none;">
            <!-- Filled by JavaScript -->
        </div>

        <p class="pro-tip" style="margin-top: 15px; background-color: #e9e5ff; border-left-color: var(--retirement-color);">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> The 4% rule is a guideline. Your actual safe withdrawal rate depends on your portfolio, time horizon, and market conditions. For early retirement (30+ years), many experts suggest 3%–3.5%.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- quiz section -->
    <div class="quiz-container animate" data-page-id="{{ page.id | default(44) }}" style="background: #1e1a3a;">
        <h3 style="color:white; margin-top: 0;">📝 Test your knowledge: The 4% Rule</h3>

        <div class="quiz-question">1. What does the 4% Rule tell you?</div>
        <div class="quiz-options" data-question="1">
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">You must save 4% of your income each year</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Your portfolio will earn exactly 4% annually</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">A safe initial withdrawal rate from your retirement savings</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">The inflation rate you should expect</div>
        </div>

        <div class="quiz-question">2. If you want to spend $50,000 per year in retirement, how much do you need saved according to the 4% rule?</div>
        <div class="quiz-options" data-question="2">
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$500,000</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$1,000,000</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">$1,250,000</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">$2,000,000</div>
        </div>

        <div class="quiz-question">3. After the first year, how should you adjust your withdrawal?</div>
        <div class="quiz-options" data-question="3">
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Withdraw the same dollar amount every year</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">Increase it by the previous year’s inflation rate</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Increase it by 4% every year</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Decrease it by inflation</div>
        </div>

        <div class="quiz-question">4. Which of the following might require a lower withdrawal rate than 4%?</div>
        <div class="quiz-options" data-question="4">
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">A 30-year retirement</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">A 40+ year retirement (e.g., early retirement)</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">A portfolio with 80% stocks</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">High inflation</div>
        </div>

        <div class="quiz-question">5. The Trinity Study assumed a portfolio of:</div>
        <div class="quiz-options" data-question="5">
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">100% stocks</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">About 60% stocks / 40% bonds</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">50% stocks / 50% cash</div>
            <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">100% bonds</div>
        </div>

        <div class="quiz-actions">
            <button id="quiz-submit" class="btn" style="background-color: var(--retirement-color);">Get score & submit</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-result"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- next steps in Phase 1 (Foundation First) -->
    <section style="margin: 60px 0;">
        <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: center;">📘 Continue Phase 1: Foundation First</h2>
        <div class="next-steps">
            <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'retirement', slug: 'retirement-basics' }) }}" class="next-card">
                <i class="fas fa-seedling"></i>
                <h3>Retirement Basics</h3>
                <p>Why starting now is your biggest advantage.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'retirement', slug: 'compound-interest' }) }}" class="next-card">
                <i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i>
                <h3>Compound Interest</h3>
                <p>The 8th wonder of the world, explained simply.</p>
            </a>
            <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'retirement', slug: 'choosing-retirement-accounts' }) }}" class="next-card">
                <i class="fas fa-piggy-bank"></i>
                <h3>401(k), IRA, Roth</h3>
                <p>Pick the right account for your situation.</p>
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>
    </div>
{% endblock %}
